to crypt height ratios within the normal range?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Patient A and B","Patient B and C","Patient C and D","Patient D and E","Patient B and E"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe normal villus to crypt height ratio in the small intestine ranges from 3:1 to 5:1. Looking at each patient:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatient A\u003C/strong\u003E has an elevated ratio of 6:1, indicating possible villous hypertrophy\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatient B\u003C/strong\u003E has a reduced ratio of 2:1, suggesting early villous atrophy\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatient C\u003C/strong\u003E has a severely reduced ratio of 1:1, indicating significant villous atrophy\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatient D\u003C/strong\u003E has a normal ratio of 4:1\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatient E\u003C/strong\u003E has a normal ratio of 3:1\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore, only Patients D and E have ratios within the normal range.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The normal villus to crypt height ratio in the small intestine is 3:1 to 5:1","Abnormal villus to crypt ratios can indicate intestinal pathology such as coeliac disease or inflammation"],"references":["Nightingale, J. M. (2012). Applied anatomy and physiology of the gastrointestinal tract (GIT). Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book: Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book, 45","Podolsky, D. K., Camilleri, M., Fitz, J. G., Kalloo, A. N., Shanahan, F., \u0026 Wang, T. C. (Eds.). (2015). Yamada\u0027s textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54757"}},"qu